For example, if you want to allow all users to read data from the `FutureMK` collection but only authenticated users with admin privileges to write to it, your Firebase security rules would look something like this:

```
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {

    // Allow any user to read from the FutureMK collection
    match /FutureMK/{document=**} {
      allow read: if true;
      allow write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.token.admin == true;
    }

    // ...
  }
}
```

In this example, the `read` rules allow anyone to access the data in the `FutureMK` collection, while the `write` rules require the user to be authenticated with an admin token to write data to the collection.

Make sure to carefully review and test your security rules before deploying them to production to ensure that they meet your application's security requirements.

